TY  - JOUR
AU  - Chowdhry, Bhagwan
T1  - What is Different about International Lending?
PY  - 1991
Y1  - 1991/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/4.1.121
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 4
IS  - 1
SP  - 121
EP  - 148
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - An attempt is made to explain how enforceability is achieved in international debt contracts. Each bank announces the policy of denying credit to borrowers who default and chooses to adhere to it to maintain its reputation of being a tough bank to discipline its other borrowers. Loans are made by syndicates of banks in order to make the penalty for default severe enough so borrowers would choose not to default voluntarily. The model predicts that the interest rate charged on loans is smaller for the larger borrowers. Also, for any given borrower, the interest rate may fall after each successive default.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/4.1.121
ER  - 



